post_text:
Aditya's NCShield.Org: Free Face Shields for Frontliners!

Triangle Senior Makes 3D-Printed Face Shields for Healthcare Workers

TMSA High School Student Aditya Shankar provides free face shields to as many healthcare and essential workers as he can in the RTP area.

He has already provided more than 150 face shields free of charge to those who risk their lives on the frontline to keep us safe against the pandemic.

When the lack of adequate PPE for frontline healthcare workers arose as a crisis, Aditya wanted to be a part of the solution and started to use his resources and skills for good.

Aditya has managed to produce face shields at a cost of $1.65. He needs your help to do more.

You can reach him at ncshield20@gmail.com or visit ncshield.org

#Healthcare #RTP #Faceshields #PPE #COVID19 #HelpHealthCareWorkers #TMSAPCS

As a young girl, Malala Yousafzai defied the Taliban in Pakistan and demanded that girls be allowed to receive an education. She was shot in the head by a Taliban gunman in 2012 but survived. In 2014, she became the youngest person to receive the Nobel Peace Prize.

post_text:
@NCPublicHealth: "Meningitis Vaccine Required All 12th Graders in NC Effective Aug. 1"

Effective Aug. 1, 2020, a booster dose of meningococcal conjugant vaccine (MenACWY) is required for students entering the 12th grade in public, private or religious schools in North Carolina. Students who do not meet this requirement may not be allowed to attend school until they receive the booster dose.

Teens and young adults are at increased risk for infection with meningococcal disease.

For more information on all vaccine requirements for 12th graders in North Carolina, go to www.immunize.nc.gov/schools.

post_text:
Dear TMSA and QCSS Communities,

Some parents have emailed us that they do not want to miss tomorrow’s deadline of Wake County Virtual Academy. As you know, our Boards will meet on Saturday to decide how to reopen our schools safely for our students and staff.

I would also remind you that Governor Cooper announced on July 14 that “[a]s a part of this plan [Plan B – Hybrid Learning], we want local school districts to provide remote learning options for any child who chooses it.” Even if our Boards decide to reopen with Plan B, we will continue to provide full remote learning for students who choose that option.

Please bear with us. Stay safe and strong!

Ben Karaduman
Superintendent

TMSA students continue making an impact on our community, even during a pandemic!

Aditya S., TMSA rising senior, has designed a way to use his 3D printer to create affordable face shields for healthcare and other essential workers.

Aditya shared, “It is called NCShield. Using the 3D printer and skills that I have developed, I am creating face shields for healthcare and essential workers. Here is the link to my website: https://sites.google.com/view/ncshield.

I have already donated face shields to UNC REX Hospital in Raleigh and Deshmukh Lab in the UNC Neuroscience Center.”

We’re so proud of his efforts and the time he is donating to serving our community. Thank you, Aditya!

post_text:
TMSA Public Charter Schools Community,

Effective immediately, all extracurricular activities, off-campus events, athletic programs (games, practices, etc.) field trips, and/or any employee-related travel is canceled until further notice.

This does not include “in-house” field trips, which do not require students to leave school. Off-campus work required for course completion is not considered a field trip. Students who are enrolled in courses that require off-campus activities as part of the course work (internships, dual credit courses) are to continue with their off-site course work, as scheduled.

We are in communication with state and county health officials. We will continue to monitor and make decisions as they are needed, and we will keep you advised. Please know that our number one priority is the safety and well-being of our students and staff. Should you have any questions, please contact the school administration.

-TMSA Admin Team, Central Office, and School Board

Exciting news from TMSA HS HOSA:

For the first time in school history, we took 25 students to the 2019 HOSA regional competition. During the day, they competed in various health related competitions. Several students and student teams placed within the top 10 in their category.

The following students placed in the top 3 and will move on to compete at the state level in April.
Chandu/Khwahish - 2nd in Forensic Science
Ronnie- 2nd in biomedical lab technique
Syeda- 1st in Dental Terminology
Matias V- 1st in Epidemiology
Sameera- 1st in Healthy Lifestyle

Congratulations to the team and the advisors!

post_text:
For the month of October we will be focusing on the character trait respect. As a family, please read our respect newsletter.

Here are a few questions you can answer as a family to help guide at home discussions about respect:

- How does it feel when someone shows disrespect?
-How can you respect others? (Parents, siblings, peers, teachers)
-What is the opposite of respect?
- How can you disagree with someone and still show respect?

post_text:
Summer Reading/Writing for Rising 6th, 7th, and 8th Graders📖📚
Summer reading time is here! Be sure to purchase and read the books listed. Additionally, there
will be written work due on the first day of school. It is imperative to complete this because the
novels will be the first unit of study in the ELA classes.
Rising 6th graders will need to purchase The Phantom Tollbooth by Norton Juster.

https://www.amazon.com/Phantom-Tollbooth-NortonJuster/dp/0394820371/ref=sr_1_1crid=1RKSQ2DG24OW1&keywords=the+phantom+tollbooth+book&qid=1559312893&s=gateway&sprefix=The+Phan%2Caps%2C131&sr=8-1
Please purchase the editions that are references in the Amazon links. Making sure all
students have the same edition helps when referencing the novel in class, and teachers will be teaching from this novel when we return to school in August.
The document with assignment details—level of annotation required, written response to
the novel, grading criteria, etc. will be available on the school’s website and the ELA
teachers’ websites by the end of the school year.
